ion your child without your assent and presence suggests one of two things to me: &#10;1) They just want to stop people homeschooling.&#10;2) They have genuinely bought the ridiculous idea that, since a child abuser *might* consider homeschooling a good idea, then all homeschooling parents must be treated as potential child abusers. &#10;At a guess I'd plump for (2) -- this government seem to treat us all as criminals that haven't been caught yet. Some of them have actually come out and said so. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="792" language="en" documentId="905" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Shadowfirebird" date="06 November 2009 3:35pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6744678" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="2" thumbsDown="0" origId="905" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="244"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="245" end="385"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="386" end="433"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="434" end="630"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="631" end="792"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>